</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[121,748,1136,1218]" lastBlockId="6.[792,1422,151,762]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[121,191,1136,1160]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Notes</emphasis>
. Hendel described this species in his genus 
<taxonomicName box="[121,274,1166,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Euxestomoea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[121,274,1166,1189]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Euxestomoea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which it somewhat resembles in wing markings and general appearance. However, the largely bare anal cell, the dorsally setulose stem vein, the one very large apical mid-tibial spur, in the male the long but unequal terminal filaments arising from a rather long bulb, and in the female the vestigial abdominal tergites 4 and 
<quantity box="[1287,1329,239,263]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
contrast to the large tergite 3, are all in contrast to 
<taxonomicName box="[1234,1376,270,293]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Euxestomoea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1234,1376,270,293]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Euxestomoea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in agreement with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="2001" box="[993,1055,299,322]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Bama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[993,1055,299,322]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Bama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[792,1422,151,762]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">
<bibRefCitation author="Hendel, F" box="[824,986,327,352]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 179" refId="ref17053" refString="Hendel, F. 1914 a. Diptera, Fam. Muscaridae, Subfam. Platystominae. Genera Insectorum 157: 1 - 179, pls 1 - 15. See McAlpine (1994) for more precise publication dates of this and next reference." type="journal article" year="1914">Hendel (1914a</bibRefCitation>
, b) illustrated and described two blackbrown dots in the distal dark zone in the first posteriormarginal cell of the wing, and these appear to be the basis of the specific epithet. These dots are present in the only male now available to me (
<figureCitation box="[1076,1136,445,469]" captionStart="Figures 1, 2" captionStartId="5.[249,321,990,1012]" captionTargetBox="[249,1366,168,970]" captionTargetId="figure-260@5.[249,1383,149,982]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 1, 2. Bama bipunctatum (Hendel). (1) Left wing of male, Sirinumu Dam. (2) Distal part of aedeagus, Sirinumu Dam, scale = 0.1 mm.bu, bulb; fs, flexible section of aedeagus; g, glans;lg, distal lobe of glans;pg, preglans;tf, terminal filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4684867" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4684867/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), but are absent in the only available female, as they are also in the female wing figured by Malloch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[792,1422,151,762]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">
Hendel described the species as having the halter yellow with black capitellum, and this is in agreement with my one available male. However Malloch described his female specimen as having the capitella (“knobs”) yellow. My female has the capitellum missing from both halteres. This character needs checking on a better series of specimens. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="2015" box="[794,948,709,733]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Bama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsi">
<emphasis box="[794,948,709,733]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Bama robertsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="2015" box="[1006,1140,709,733]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Bama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divergens">
<emphasis box="[1006,1140,709,733]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">B. divergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the only other known species of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="2001" box="[1051,1113,739,762]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Bama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1051,1113,739,762]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Bama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with dark capitellum.
</paragraph>
